ased","1080–1137":"1080–1137","–1098":"–1098","1010–1064":"1010–1064","1080":"1080","after 30 April 1096":"after 30 April 1096","1098":"1098","1010":"1010","1075":"1075","1064":"1064","1063":"1063","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","Abt 1075":"about 1075","1137":"1137","1016":"1016","before 1064":"before 1064","Aft 1098":"after 1098","Abt 1050":"about 1050","Abt 1080":"about 1080","Of,,,France":"France","France, Centre, Sully-sur-Loire":"Sully-sur-Loire, Loiret, Centre-Val de Loire, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sully","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armelle, Christophe, Geralde, Luce, Pierre, Reynald.","English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from any of the three places called Sully in Calvados (Normandy), Aisne (Picardy), and Loiret (Centre); see 6 below.","English: of Norman origin, perhaps a habitational name from Sully (Glamorgan). However, the placename is manorial in origin, from the Norman surname in 1 above, which is recorded in Glamorgan in the 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Soley","meanings":["English: variant of   Sully  .","Catalan: variant of <b>Solell</b>, a topographic name from <i>solell</i> ‘sunny side, southern slope’, from a derivative of <i>sol</i> ‘sun’. Compare   Sol   2."]},{"name":"Solley","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Sully  ."]},{"name":"Solly","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Sully  .","Irish: variant of   Salley  ."]}]},{"name":"Giles","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Much altered English vernacular form of the Late Latin name <i>Aegidius</i>, from Greek <i>Aigidios</i> (a derivative of <i>aigidion</i> ‘kid, young goat’), via Old French <i>Gide</i>. It was the name of an 8th‐century saint who, according to tradition, was an Athenian citizen who fled to Provence because he could not cope with the fame and adulation caused by his power to work miracles, in particular by healing the lame and crippled. This was not a particularly common name in the Middle Ages and its use seems to have been confined to certain families and localities."],"variants":[{"name":"Gyles","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Giles ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Giles de Sully was born about 1050, his father, Archambaud de Sully II,  Seigneur de Sully, was 36 and his mother, Agnès, was 42. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Eldeberge Bourges. He died after 1098."},"et":{"Abt 1050–Aft 1098":"umbes 1050–pärast 1098","1016–1064":"1016–1064","1050–1098":"1050–1098","–1064":"–1064","–1070":"–1070","–Male":"Surnud","1050–1096":"1050–1096","1075–Female":"1075–Surnud","1080–1137":"1080–1137","–1098":"–1098","1010–1064":"1010–1064","1080":"1080","after 30 April 1096":"pärast 30. aprilli 1096","1098":"1098","1010":"1010","1075":"1075","1064":"1064","1063":"1063","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","1070":"1070","Abt 1075":"umbes 1075","1137":"1137","1016":"1016","before 1064":"enne 1064","Aft 1098":"pärast 1098","Abt 1050":"umbes 1050","Abt 1080":"umbes 1080","Of,,,France":"Prantsusmaa","France, Centre, Sully-sur-Loire":"Sully-sur-Loire, Loiret, Centre-Val de Loire, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1050–Aft 1098":"noin 1050–10